.TH SHH 28 "December 2025" "shh 1.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
shh \- hide files inside PNG images using steganography
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B shh hide
.I image.png secret output
.br
.B shh decode
.I input output
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B shh
is a steganography tool that hides files inside PNG images.
Data is appended after the PNG IEND chunk, making the image
appear normal while containing hidden content.
.PP
When hiding with a password, data is encrypted using AES-256-CBC
with PBKDF2 key derivation (100,000 iterations).
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B hide
Hide a file inside a PNG image. Creates two output files:
.I output.png
(the stego image) and
.I output.txt
(base64 encoded version for safe upload).
Password is optional (press Enter to skip).
.TP
.B decode
Extract hidden file from a stego image. Accepts both PNG and
base64 encoded TXT as input. Auto-detects format.
.SH EXAMPLES
Hide a file without password:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ shh hide photo.png secret.html output
Password: [Enter]
.fi
.RE
.PP
Hide a file with password:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ shh hide photo.png secret.pdf output
Password: ********
Confirm: ********
.fi
.RE
.PP
Extract from PNG:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ shh decode output.png extracted
$ file extracted
extracted: HTML document, ASCII text
$ mv extracted extracted.html
.fi
.RE
.PP
Extract from base64:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ shh decode output.txt extracted
Password: ********
$ file extracted
extracted: PDF document, version 1.4
$ mv extracted extracted.pdf
.fi
.RE
.SH SECURITY
.TP
.B Encryption
AES-256-CBC with random salt and IV
.TP
.B Key Derivation
PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256 with 100,000 iterations
.TP
.B Password
Not echoed to terminal
.SH FILES
.TP
.I output.png
Stego image (valid PNG with hidden data)
.TP
.I output.txt
Base64 encoded stego image (for upload to services that re-encode images)
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Error (wrong password, file not found, etc.)
.SH NOTES
The hidden data is appended after the PNG IEND chunk.
Image viewers only read up to IEND, so the image displays normally.
.PP
Some services (Facebook, Twitter, etc.) re-encode uploaded images,
which removes hidden data. Use the base64 TXT output for text-based
sharing, or upload to services that preserve original files.
